{
  "texts": [
    "It is thus possible for traits that are more important determinants of fertilisation success to evolve slower rates of senescence than less important traits 63, which future studies could test.",
    "We discovered some taxonomic class-specific evidence for agedependent changes in individual ejaculate traits.",
    "Insects showed an increase in all sperm and ejaculate quantity traits.",
    "This increase could be associated with their mating status, as most studies (>75%) on insects in our meta-analysis kept males as virgins.",
    "Specifically, in species with life-long spermatogenesis and low rates of sperm loss (such as some insects 64, 65), low mating rates can result in old males accumulating more sperm and producing larger ejaculates than young males 66."
  ]
}